+        "side": "RIGHT"
+      },
+      "risk_if_unchanged": "A single bad row with a large string or blob can allocate and retain a multi-megabyte error message until the chunk/job unwinds, causing avoidable memory spikes or OOM on the failure path instead of failing predictably.",
+      "evidence": "Both encode implementations explicitly defer `TruncateWarns()` because conversion errors can keep the parser buffer alive (`sql2kv.go:218-222`, `kv_encode.go:90-94`). The new code then calls `datumToValueStringForCastError(original)` with no size cap and feeds that into `ErrCastValue` (`base.go:359-361`). For `KindBytes` it first materializes a string and then lets `DatumsToStringSmart` render the full payload, including hex output for binary data.",
